	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Columbus, Ohio - Origins 2005<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11045'>Patrick "Patrick M. S" Sullivan</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11045&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> July 6, 2006</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font class="bfont"> Note from me: Hey all, I’d been meaning to do this for sometime now. I wanted to move all my Tournament Reports from the Decipher and DGMA sites to Decktech and Gameplayersnetwork since they are easier to find here and I’m worried that Decipher’s two sites will go down eventually. I wouldn’t want to lose all these awesome memories. So here they are, archived, for your amusement. Feel free to give reviews with your thoughts and memories of the events or to simply let me know how you liked the read. <br />
<br />
Mr. Sullivan goes to Origins for a third time<br />
<br />
Thursday, June 30th to Sunday, July 3th, 2005<br />
<br />
Pre-tourney Jank<br />
<br />
So after the shellacking my Noble Leaders fellowship received from those tough-as-nails Europeans in Holland two weeks ago, I decided to try something that can survive a little longer and that can handle burdens. I ran into quite a bit of trouble against Enquea Burden shadows so I decided to build a Hobbit fellowship with Wingchow (Aragorn, Wingfoot) as my site manipulator and giver-of-double-moves. This would mean playing Prancing Pony, Anduril and 4x Pathfinder. I decided to keep the same Forest Nazgul build as I played in Holland since they never failed to disappoint. In fact, I’m even adding a Nertea, Thrall of the One, to perhaps nab at site 2 kill against some ill prepared fellowships. <br />
<br />
However, that deck will only be used for the Continental Championships on Sunday and perhaps during the PSQ on Saturday. Only those events will be Standard Format. The main event, the PSE, will be expanded format. The only place I have played expanded format is online. I have been faithfully playing the exact same expanded deck over the last 3 months. It was a basic Dworc deck (meaning Dwarves and Morgul Orcs) that is focused on underground sites so that Till Durin Wakes Again completely heals up my fellowship to stack tons of skirmish events on Preparations that Sindri replays. I have been doing very well with it but the deck, even with the Smeagol/Follow Smeagol package, loses to burden Nazgul. In Holland, I raised this concern to my friend, Fred Lafont from France. He convinced me after playing a game against his deck, that burden nazgul is unstoppable. Playing Enquea, Thrall of the One with Fellowship block Toldea and Bill Ferny abusing Sense of Obligation is just too strong a combo to pass up. So I go home and build this deck even though I do not own 4x Between Nazgul and Prey. I have only 3, so I splash in Bill Ferny who I think will do well in that deck. <br />
<br />
For the fellowship, on Fred’s advice, I am playing a filtering Gandalf/Ent fellowship that plays lots of Wizard is Never Late and Saved by the Fire to completely filter out the fellowship so I can get my shadow corruption as fast as possible. I decided to splash in Elrond, Lord of Rivendell and Ottar, Man of Laketown to help cycle into the good stuff and set up god-hands of shadow. Finally, just because we’re allowed, I threw in one copy of Bill the Pony just because I miss him. Talk about a waste of a card slot. I had to completely liquidate all my Servant of the Secret Fires to make room for those three cards. Hope it pays off. <br />
<br />
So with these two decks ready to rock Ohio, I pack them up and a few days of clothes (ncluding the usual contingent of DGMA tournament T-shirts) and head out to Columbus. I’m booked on a 7pm flight Thursday night arriving in Columbus just before midnight after making a pitstop in Toronto. I’m staying at the Holiday Inn right beside the convention centre with Ryan Connor, Phil French and Chris Schoenthal! I’m a little worried about it since I haven’t heard anything from Ryan at all and haven’t heard from Phil in a while either. I just hope everyone shows up otherwise the hotel could be a little pricey. <br />
<br />
Day Zero<br />
Thursday, June 30th, 2005<br />
<br />
The night before, I host a 6-player tournament at a new retailer, Gamers’ World in Montreal. I decide to make it expanded since I need to practice my corruption deck at some point. It’s a cool new store with tons of video games and computers and I think I might try my luck at the Battlefield 2 ladder tournament starting on July 18th. Anyway I go 3-0 with the Expanded corruption deck but it wasn’t that easy. So I think I might be in some trouble if I can barely win a local tournament with it. <br />
<br />
So after work on the Thursday I drive out to the airport and part in the Econo-park 7$ parking lot where I have to take a shuttle bus to the airport. I have about an hour before my flight when I park my car so I gotta hustle. However, upon exiting the car, I notice a loud SHHHHHH noise. I then see that my left back tire is rapidly losing air. I can’t do anything about it now so I call my friend, Scot, to make sure that leaving a car with a flat won’t ruin the axle, brake drum or any other random car part I know nothing about. He says no so I go to catch the plane looking forward to changing my first flat tire when I get back. It better not rain. <br />
<br />
So my plane to Toronto is 1 hour late which makes me super nervous about getting there on time. So I knock back a ham & cheese sandwich, yogourt and awful orange juice trying to get my mind off missing the connection. When I arrive in Toronto, the airport is under construction and getting around is hell. I have to take TWO buses to get to my terminal where my small turboprop airplane is waiting. I have to go through U.S. customs first and I’m crazy stressed out about missing my flight. The officer asks me what the purpose of my trip is. I say, “there’s a card tournament there.” He says, “and why would you want to do that?” I think about it for a sec and say, “To win?” I don’t know if that was my best answer but it gets me waved through.<br />
<br />
It takes me almost an hour to get to the gate and I figure I missed the flight but it too is running 90 minutes late so I make it in time. I have to kill time so I sit and have two double scotches with some guy, Alex,  who flying to Columbus to pick up a Saab 900 convertible to drive back to Montreal. I’m kinda jealous cuz that sounds like fun. He asks me why I’m going to Columbus and I say for a big card tournament. He asks, “poker?” and I say, “sure.” He then buys me another double scotch while I tell him the dangers of pocket jacks. <br />
<br />
So the plane is a Bombardier (yay, Quebec company) Dash-8. Haven’t been on a prop plane since flying out to Spokane for the DPC a few years back. There’s two cute girls sitting in front of me and one of them is blowing up one of those pillows that goes around your neck. I lean in and ask, “is that a life jacket?” to which she laughs and feel like a total moron for not thinking of something cooler to say. <br />
<br />
Anyway, I get into Columbus after 1 in the morning and catch a cab to the hotel. There, I’m not surprised to find Chris Schoenthal from California and only him. The other two didn’t show up so this room is going to cost Chris and I 550 bucks. I’ll stomach 350 of it since it’s mostly my fault and cuz I’m staying an extra night Sunday. <br />
<br />
Day One<br />
Friday, July 1st, 2005<br />
CANADA DAY!<br />
<br />
So I head downstairs with Chris Schoenthal and order up the All-American Skillet for my Canada Day breakfast. It’s pretty good but the whole breakfast ends up setting me back 15 bucks. Youch. We grab the free shuttle to the convention (since the hotel is like 2 miles away) and I sign up for Day One of the PSE. I am really lacking confidence in my expanded deck since I barely won my local on Wednesday night but I’m feeling in pretty good shape with tons of coffee in my system so let’s get to work!<br />
<br />
34 people show up for this event making it very sparsely attended. I’m immediately worried that not making top 16 is going to be really embrassing but then again, it’s Origins and there’s a ton of fun stuff to do. <br />
<br />
Round: One  <br />
Opponent: Earned Bye<br />
Result FW <br />
1-0<br />
<br />
whew, so far so good.<br />
<br />
Round: Two<br />
Opponent: Eventual PSE winner, Jonathan Benton<br />
Deck: Turbo Enquea Corruption / Dwarf-Smeagol<br />
Good: Benton is a crazy nice opponent. Always smiling.<br />
Bad: Both are shadows are really scary to play against<br />
Ugly: I have 2 All blades Perish against Smeagol which ends up allowing Toldea to kill Smeagol and then corrupt in the fierce skirmish by assigning to someone who doesn’t have Sense of Obligation on him<br />
Result: FW Corruption site 8<br />
2-0<br />
<br />
Round: Three<br />
Opponent: Steve Minard<br />
Deck: Dwarf-Smeagol / Moria<br />
Good: Not only is this my best match-up but Steve is also a real nice guy. Fun to play against.<br />
Bad: It’s a pretty dismal match up for him. <br />
Ugly: All his shadow conditions are gone and my Toldea is working his fellowship like a dog<br />
Result: FW site 5 corruption<br />
3-0<br />
<br />
So already with a 3-0 record, I THINK I’m in top 16 but I better win one more to be sure.<br />
<br />
Round: Four<br />
Opponent: Mike Noonan!<br />
Deck: Elf-Man Archery / Dunland<br />
Good: Mike rocks. I don’t know how I always get stuck playing him in every single event I attend.<br />
Bad: This was SUCH a hard fellowship to corrupt<br />
Ugly: I slam Toldea on Samwise the Brave the second he gets played but Mike didn’t discard Salt of the Shire to go down to 3 burdens. I don’t think I could have won this match otherwise<br />
Result: FW site 8 corruption<br />
4-0<br />
<br />
Yay, I made top 16! Phew. It’s too funny that my only three red DGMA pins are all from Origins. I always make day two PSE Origins but can’t seem to pull that off anywhere else.<br />
<br />
Round: Five<br />
Opponent: Emir Delic!<br />
Deck: Dwarf/Smeagol/Greenleaf  - Forest Nazgul with Keening Wail<br />
Good: Emir uses his World Championship trophy as his site marker<br />
Bad: This couldn’t be a worse match-up for Emir<br />
Ugly: I get perfect draws at sites 2 and 3<br />
Result: FW site 3 corruption<br />
5-0<br />
<br />
This game ends very early so Emir and I go get a drink. Alex K from Toronto tells us this hilarious story in how during his game, his opponent is starting to look sick and asks to borrow Alex’s bag. Alex hands it to him and the guy makes sick all over the place. Not much of a basketball player after mostly missing the bag. Anyway, the cleaning guy comes over, looks at the mess and says, “I’m not cleaning that.” His boss was there and says, “you clean that up or you’re fired.” To which the guy throws his broom in his supervisor’s face and says, “fine! I quit!”  High drama at the Origins Convention Centre.<br />
<br />
Round: Six<br />
Opponent: Edwin Harris! <br />
Deck: Hobbit-gandalf-smeagol-wingchow / uruk swarm<br />
Good: Young Edwin and I at top table in this last round is just too cool for words. I remember playing Edwin a long time ago when he had big puffy hair and was spilling huge sodas on other people’s games. Now he’s a champ J<br />
Bad: This was actually a HARD matchup for me in terms of killing his fellowship. Buckland Homestead was HUGE in this game.<br />
Ugly:  Samwise comes to the rescue and I slam Helpless on him and kill him immediately with Toldea. Too funny.<br />
Result: FW corruption site 5<br />
6-0!<br />
<br />
Ahhh! I went 6-0 placing 1st in a Day One PSE and on Canada Day of all days! Take THAT, Mike French! J<br />
<br />
So after grabbing some really good prize support, Chris Schoe, Kirk England, Matt Ward and Chuck Ward all head off to O’Shaunessey’s Irish Pub. Chris and I order some dang fine chicken fingers, rarebit (look it up), and two pulled pork sandwiches. I get half the sandwich on my shorts and decide that we ordered too much food. Oh, and I ordered a soup too I think. Have a pint of cider but I’m not feeling so well so we call it an early night. We then pop on over to the Italian restaurant next door where Kim Logie, Jim Colson, Hayden and their crew are hanging out. We leave Kirk there and Chris and I head back to the hotel in a cab with the Wards. It ends up only being 4 bucks so I pick up the bill. This city has the cheapest cabs ever. The cab from the airport was less than 25 bucks! Every city I’ve ever been to is almost always 40 dollars from the airport. <br />
<br />
So Chris Schoenthal and I decide to hit up the pool. We both jump in and start splashing around like idiots. We exchange a glance at one point after spotting a fairly unattractive girl walking by in a bathing soon way too small for her. Pretty funny stuff. Then explosions start and we figure it’s another attack but turns out it’s fireworks so we head upstairs to get a better look from the room. You gotta hand it to the Yanks... they do a pretty fine job at blowing up the sky. It was very pretty. <br />
<br />
So we kick everyone out of the room and Chris really wants to make a decklist but Crimson Tide just started and he gets sucked into the movie after watching only a few minutes. We watch the whole thing then off to bed. <br />
<br />
<br />
Day Two<br />
Saturday, July 2nd, 2005<br />
<br />
So I had set the wake up call relatively late but the phone rings really early (like around 7 or 8 or something). I answer and it’s Kirk. He asks, “So you wanna drive out to MacDonald’s and Tim Horton’s with me?”  DO I?! I pop in the shower and run downstairs and the two of us drive off. We have a grand old time where he orders the Big Breakfast and I go with the old stand-by, The Sausage McGriddle. I stupidly order a coffee forgetting we’re going to Tim Horton’s after (that’s Canada’s best coffee shop named after a hockey player of course). So I ditch my crappy MacDonald’s coffee and upgrade that baby for a medium double-double (which in the States is a large for some strange reason) and we’re off to the convention centre once again, driving by Brad Eier’s university on the way. <br />
<br />
So turns out that the beautiful Dan Clark would rather play Versus than play in Day Two LOTR PSE so he drops out which gets Steve Jones in 16th place which is my first round opponent. I hate playing people I like so much but it’s a mixed blessing since at least you’re not losing to someone you dislike. Beating them isn’t as much fun though as beating someone you don’t know well. Anyway, I’m sure it’ll be a friendly game so have at thee!<br />
<br />
Match One<br />
Round: One<br />
Opponent: Steve Jones<br />
Deck: Dwarf-Smeagol-Greenleaf / Somridil’s Southron Archery<br />
Good: When my corruption nazgul rocks the mike, they rock the mike right<br />
Bad: I have a terrible starting hand but draw into a PERFECT mulligan. <br />
Ugly: I get both my Minas Morgul Answers by site 4 which is SO essential against this match-up.<br />
Result: FW corruption site 4<br />
1-0<br />
<br />
Round: Two<br />
Good: We both bid 1, tie and he makes me start I think. He then doesn’t start Smeagol.<br />
Bad: I Kill Linnar and regret it. I need two unbounds on the table to do anything<br />
Ugly: He’s choking me like mad but I eventually get him<br />
Result: FW corruption site 8<br />
2-0<br />
<br />
After beating Steve, I offer to buy him a drink and then completely forget about it. <br />
So after winning my first match against my buddy, Jones, I move on to the juggernaught, Benton. I’m not initially worried about this at all since I beat him good yesterday and hoping he’s playing the same deck.<br />
<br />
Match Two<br />
Round: One<br />
Opponent: Jonathan Benton<br />
Deck: 2 site control Dunland / Dwarf-Smeagol<br />
Good: Benton’s still a nice guy to play against and both our shadows are very strong. It’s going to be a shadow kill/corruption game for sure. <br />
Bad: I can’t seem to corrupt him at site 5 and I’m only one burden away. <br />
Ugly: Instead of fetching 2 Travelled Leaders with a Saved from the Fire, I instead fetch Deep in Thought as per Steve Jones’ suggestion before the game. He ends up spending ALL the pool so I can’t Deep in Thought away his No Retreat. If I had fetched the Travelled Leaders I could have played Heights of Isengard to discard No Retreat and corrupt him at the next site. But instead, I’m forced to double L<br />
Result: FL shadow kill site 6<br />
0-1<br />
<br />
Round: Two<br />
Good: He doesn’t get into Hides for a long time which buys my shadow a lot of time to do its thing<br />
Bad: I mulligan and draw into 3 Enquea <br />
Ugly: All the support cards for Enquea only show up in the last 3 sites.<br />
Result: FL shadow kill from No Retreat site 8<br />
0-2<br />
<br />
So Benton knocks me out and moves on to win the whole thing. That shadow was very scary stuff. So I’ve got 3 hours or so to kill until the 6pm PSQ so I start thinking up stuff to do. I find out that William Hung (from American Idol) is playing Pokemon so I walk over and shake his hand. I get the feeling he’s kinda sick of people coming up to him so I leave him alone. Reed Mascola gets him to sign his foil Elf Song tho. Nice job. I find it crazy weird that Hung would come to the Pokemon championship where he’s obviously going to be recognized. It’s kind of a hassle being a celebrity cuz everyone just comes up to you. I don’t know if I’d want to be going to CCG tournaments if I were some big celebrity but I think it’s kinda cool that he’s going it. His mom is with him and at one point she makes him his lunch and they then eat together. His mom seems real nice and smiles a lot but watching her make his lunch makes me half really sad and half really envious. I can’t remember the last time someone made me lunch. Life sure was easier then. So I decide to go get my own lunch before I get more sad. <br />
<br />
So I cross the street and go to a brew pub called Barley’s. There I order another double scotch (18-year Glenlivet, yum) and a half order of chicken wings with a pulled pork sandwich with tater tots! I couldn’t resist ordering Napoleon Dynamite’s favourite snack. I was half hoping someone I knew would walk in and try to steal one so I could smack them, pull my tater tots away and say, “Get your own! I haven’t had anything to eat all day!” But alas no one comes. I can’t remember tater tots ever being this good though when I was a kid.<br />
<br />
Anyway, this drunk guy comes in and sits at the bar and orders a big plate of nachos. The bartender brings him his nachos and people at the bar nicely wish the guy good luck in getting through that plate. He’s about half-way through when he tells the bartender in a slurred accent that he’s going to go to the bank machine to get some money. The bartender says ‘just a sec’ and goes and talks to the manager. He comes back and tells the guy he has to leave some I.D. The guy says (again slurs) that he needs his I.D. to take out money. The bartender against says, ‘just a sec’ and talks to his manager. This time they both come back and tell the guy he has to leave his I.D. At this point the guy gets agitated and starts talking real loud about how he’s good for it and will come back to pay. The restaurant managers are adamant about him leaving behind I.D. and a big argument takes place. Now, at this point, if it was MY restaurant, I would stomach the 6.99$ loss on the nachos and let the guy go but they insist on giving him a hard time. And it’s clearly making all the clients (including me) really uncomfortable. Some people start to leave and I can’t believe they aren’t just letting this guy go and telling him not to come back. Problem solved, right? Well, one of the managers then comes back and tells a waiter, “Can you go check on that take out order?” To which the waiter responds, “... what?” and the manager repeats, “Can you go check on that take out order?” and the waiter goes, “Oh.. yeah. Sure, I’m on it.”  Now if that isn’t a more obvious code for call-the-cops, I don’t know what is. And sure enough the cops come and pull the guy to the side and another big argument takes place and I decide to take my leave of the restaurant which I feel is ran by a bunch of dummies. I half want to ask the guy if he wants my I.D. when I go to the bathroom but decide against it. <br />
<br />
I then head back to the convention centre and stop by the Decipher booth. I forgot to mention that I demoed a game of Trek 2nd edition earlier that day. It was good fun. Lots more thinking than I thought was involved. Anyway, they have the entire Bloodlines set printed out and hung up in card protectors. I quickly find my favourite one, Softly Up Behind, and pull out a marker and sign it. <br />
<br />
So I still got time to kill so since the convention hall is SO cold and ultra air-conditioned, I’ve been stepping outside often since the weather was so beautiful that day. Instead of walking around to one of the main entrance/exits, I usually just poked out back from the Tournament Hall’s service exit. I then prop open the door so it doesn’t lock shut when I walk out and stand outside. I did this numerous times with Dan Jones and my friend Mikael Lane from Quebec. This one time, the Origins official pokes his head out the door while we’re out there and says, “Do you see the sign Entrance here?” while pointing to the door we walked out of which has no handles or anything written on it. He then continues, “No? I didn’t think so!” He then awkwardly fixes the door so it isn’t propped open and slams it shut so that we have to walk around the building to get back in. <br />
<br />
Anyway, I thought it was pretty funny since we kept going outside anyway through that service door. So at one point, a bunch of us are outside and I tell the guys about this power-trippy Origins official. I then show them what he did but going back to that same door with Dan Jones, Mike Noonan and others outside and I start to say, “See this door? Do you see Entrance written on it?!” I then start to fidget with the door trying to get it ready to slam when I sense someone behind me. I turn around and the very same Origins official is glaring at me with this silly grin. I quickly say, “I’ll just show myself out.” And pull the door locked behind me. Pretty funny J<br />
<br />
So the Standard PSQ finally gets underway so I give my 4 Origins game tokens as payment and we start up a 5-round tournament at around 7pm. Good thing I’m not tired just yet. I pull out my Hobbit/Wingchow with Forest Nazgul deck and get ready to rock. <br />
<br />
Round: One<br />
Opponent: Chris “F.U.” Schoenthal<br />
Deck: Underground orc swarm / Dwarf-Smeagol<br />
Good: Chris rocks and I like how he initials scoresheets<br />
Ugly: Chris’ shadow did nothing but he did stay in a Holiday Inn last night<br />
Result: FW site 9. It’s good to be playing a fellowship winning deck again.<br />
1-0<br />
<br />
I offer to buy Chris a drink and don’t forget this time so we go off for coffee and mountain dew. When we get back, the games are still going on so Chris and I set up behind Steve Jones’ game against Reed’s friend Paul and start a little song and dance:<br />
<br />
“You can drink your fancy ales. <br />
You can drink them by the falgon.<br />
But the only brew for the strong and truuuuue....<br />
...comes from the Green Dragon!”<br />
<br />
At the end of which I wanted to recreate the spilling of the drink so I kick Paul’s chair with my open toe sandal and injure myself being the idiot that I am L<br />
<br />
Round: Two<br />
Opponent: Steve Jones for the 3rd game today<br />
Deck: Hobbit-Smeagol / Forest Nazzies<br />
Good: Steve is fun and he’s playing the Smeagol that cycles I think so I don’t have to worry.<br />
Bad: We both have 4 Sudden Fury out so 8 of these in one game takes LONG and a lot of tokens<br />
Ugly With 16 seconds left on the clock, I single into 9 with 9 companions<br />
Result: FW site 9<br />
2-0<br />
<br />
Round: Three<br />
Opponent: Seth Maser! The Godfather of Somridil himself coming after me after I just took out two of his minions<br />
Deck: Southrons (of course) with Elf-Eowyn<br />
Good: This was a nice and quiet match<br />
Bad: He gets no shadow until site 6 or 7<br />
Ugly: I then play 3 pathfinders at 7, 8 and 9 to heal up and avoid Anduin Banks<br />
Result: FW site 9<br />
3-0<br />
<br />
Round: Four<br />
Opponent: Dan Jones (Steve’s brother) <br />
Deck: Lurker swarm / Noble Leaders<br />
Good: Dan’s a great big friendly guy<br />
Bad: I don’t know how to play against Lurker swarm. I double move which is dumb since I should only stay one site ahead so I can replace the current site using Nelya so he never gets to use his Goblin Hordes<br />
Ugly: The end of this game turned really ugly which is really unfortunate. The game is running low on time but neither of us are too stressed about that. I move to site 8 and Dan drops a huge swarm on me. 3 guys get assigned to Sam. I still have lots of companionsbut Frodo is dead. It looks like time is going to run out at this site. Anyway, Sam finds himself with 3 or 4 guys on him but Rosie is still in play so he needs to triple Sam’s strength to overwhelm (he needs 39 strength I think). There is currently 34 on Sam. I get the feeling that Dan doesn’t know what Rosie does exactly so I need to get him to pass his skirmish action so that I can just take a burden and survive. He has enough pool to pump his guys a lot but I also have 4 or 5 tokens on Sudden Fury. I should probably have looked if Sam could survive with what was on the table but I want Dan to quickly pass instead since if I look and start counting he’ll know something is up. So I say, “I pass.” And he looks politely at me and says, “So... he dies?” Now at this point, I’m not considering that as him passing his action. I’m told later that could have counted as a pass but I didn’t want to risk it. So I still need to get Dan to pass so I respond, “apparently Sam is overwhelmed” or something like that. Whatever I say is completely false cuz I feel that Dan should be able to read the board and figure out that Sam isn’t overwhelmed. Anyway everything is fine until Dan then says, “ok, I’ll pass” and I point out Rosie and take a burden. Things get really ugly really fast at this point and I’m being told that I lied and misrepresented the game situation and all this. I’m trying to explain that I’m trying to get him to pass and I don’t know how to do that without accidentally spoonfeeding him the way to overwhelm Sam. All the cards are on the table. Anyway, a shouting match begins and Paul Holbrook and Chris S try to calm us down but we’re both pretty adamant about our positions and the arguing continues. The two tragic parts of this are 1) Dan Jones is a really good friend and 2) there is a TON of people including kids watching the game. I guess I was a pretty crappy dAgent at that moment. Anyway, some people were on my side and some where on his side but in the end, Paul Holbrook (Level 4 judge) had to the game that went to time and I got a timed win. I apologized afterwards trying to smooth things over but to no avail. Hopefully tomorrow things will be ok.<br />
Result: TW site 8<br />
4-0<br />
<br />
Round: Five<br />
Opponent: Dave Evans! I’ve never played him so I’m hoping it’ll be friendly and quiet enough to distract me from my last game cuz I’m clearly on tilt.<br />
Deck: Noble Leaders / Forest Nazgul – Oh man, a deck I actually really have to think about playing against. <br />
Good: Dave couldn’t have been anymore relaxed of an opponent. It’s exactly what I needed<br />
Bad: I was so bummed out about my last game that I couldn’t concentrate. Dave kept talking to me and asking me stuff but I couldn’t focus and kept drifting off. <br />
Ugly: Playing 8 hobbits with Wingchow versus forest nazgul is actually decent for the hobbits. I thought this would be a bad match up but it was pretty good. <br />
Result: FW, Dave concedes at site 8<br />
5-0<br />
<br />
So I go undefeated but it’s bittersweet as you can well imagine so I grab my prizes which consists of an Italian box of Siege of Gondor boosters and join Hayden and Dawn at the Char Bar for some drinks and laughs. <br />
<br />
It takes me all of 10 minutes to unwind and I got 2 Hardcore ciders in my system (best cider ever and it’s American!) before I know what hit me. Hayden and I laugh it up quite a bit and I finally get the chance to get to know this guy who edited my Tournament Reports for years (well, months anyway). Talking with Hayden was easier than talking to Dawn’s friends from another company who I couldn’t really relate to. <br />
<br />
After a couple drinks I head back to the convention centre where Mike Girard, Mike Noonan are in a poker tournament. It’s too late for me to join so I sit with Charles Hickey and a few of his friends who are having a cash game. I buy in for 8 bucks which is pretty pathetic for 0.50/1.00 No Limit hold em but I want to feel out the table first. These guys are really comfortable and can triple chop a pot in a few seconds so I know that I’m playing with people that know what they’re doing. This young guy, Alex, is taking everyone’s money, it’s pretty cool. I end up only winning pots where Hickey (who sits to my right) was betting into me. Pretty good stuff. I end up doubling my money after going all in and call it a night after Mike Noonan chops his tournament prize with Mike Girard. <br />
<br />
Mike and I then walk the two miles back to the hotel which wasn’t so bad. I then fall fast asleep after listening to the iPod for a bit. <br />
<br />
Day Three<br />
Sunday, July 3rd, 2005<br />
<br />
So once again Kirk wakes me up with that awesome offer of Macdonald’s and Tim Horton’s. This time Paul Holbrook joins us. This time I just go for the Sausage McMuffin with orange juice. The latter was gross but the former was dee-lish. My coffee cup from Timmy’s leaks like crazy though so I’m drinking it as fast as possible before I lose it all on my lap. <br />
<br />
We get to the convention hall in plenty of time and I get to watch some of Day Two WARS play-off. I’m hoping that Mike Lane from Montreal will win but he seems to be running into some trouble and doesn’t make it. <br />
<br />
So after winning the PSQ last night, I’m decide to stick to my hobbits with Forest Nazgul. I’m doubtful that I’ll pull it off with them but figure I have no choice since I left my other decks back at the hotel. <br />
<br />
I walk around the playing area and see Dan Jones with Steve Jones and Mike Noonan. I don’t know if they’re still mad or what and I feel pretty awkward about the whole thing so I just avoid them.<br />
<br />
Round: One<br />
Opponent: Eventual 2nd placing 16-year old Adrian Westico<br />
Deck: Forest Nazgul / Noble Leaders – the deck I brought to Holland. <br />
Good: This is Adrian’s 1st time playing that deck which gives me a huge advantage since I know the deck even better than he does.<br />
Bad: He lets me draw cards at site 3 with Denethor and I draw into mostly fellowship. He plays Elendil with Narsil and I’m pretty worried since I’m at site 5 or 6 and he can now catch up. But I played the Angle at site 5 and he knows he’ll get into trouble if he moves there. <br />
Ugly: I can’t get my Nelyas out all game to bounce back my Valley of the Silverlode which is THE winning card for hobbits against forest nazgul<br />
Result: FW site 9<br />
1-0<br />
<br />
Round: Two<br />
Opponent: Mike Noonan AGAIN<br />
Deck: Noble leaders with Grown Suddenly Tall / Corsair initiative wind/Fierce in Despair<br />
Good: This is really a good match up against my deck<br />
Bad: Mike uses Denethor 4 times so that I get 16 cards and he smartly picks out 2 Saplings which are essential for his deck<br />
Ugly: He doesn’t get Fierce in Despair when he most needs it<br />
Result: FW site 9<br />
2-0<br />
<br />
Mike then tells me it’s cool to go up and talk to them (Steve, him and Dan) and that I don’t need to avoid them or anything. That makes me feel slightly better but I’m more concerned about how Dan feels so I still avoid the whole lot of them. <br />
<br />
Round: Three<br />
Opponent: Christian “Sting” Keissel<br />
Deck: Corsairs with Red Wrath /  Gandwarf<br />
Good: This is an excellent match up for my deck if I play it smart<br />
Bad: I’m scared at site 2 that he might have a Red Wrath so I sacrifice Tolman Cotton just in case to protect Sam.<br />
Ugly: I get out 4x Sudden Fury and 4x Lost in the Woods by site 3<br />
Result: FW site 9<br />
3-0<br />
<br />
At this point right before the next round, Dan and I cross each other between tables and wishes me luck for my next game. That makes me feel way better and I naturally reciprocate the wish of good luck. <br />
<br />
Round: Four<br />
Opponent: Kyle George who I always forget that I played before<br />
Deck: Turbo super-ultra corruption nazgul / dwarf-smeagol<br />
Good: Kyle is not only lots of fun but is ridiculously fast which is awesome<br />
Bad:  Even though I get to site 8 in less than 20 minutes, I have no idea how to play against this shadow with hobbits so I just ran like mad. <br />
Ugly: I ran as fast as I could and he still got 13 burdens on me<br />
Result: FL shadow corrupt site 8<br />
3-1<br />
<br />
I got outside for some fresh air after losing so fast and sit in the grass and listen to my iPod (I’m totally addicted to listening to this beautiful country music singer from Montreal, Angela Desveaux). Everything is going peachy and I’m watching these two big fellas try to take this huge refridgerator-looking cabinet out of their pickup truck when the thing comes crashing down on the big guy’s foot. He collapses in pain on the grass and it looks like he broke his foot pretty good. His friend runs off to get help and I try to get inside to get some water since the guy is lying in the grass in the sun and it’s scortching hot outside. Well, I had left the door propped open and guess who shows up? Yup, that Origins official who looks ready to rip my head off but I tell him there’s a medical emergency and he needs to come with his walkie-talkie and so we run out together to help out this guy. The guy is just in a lot of pain and doesn’t appear to be too seriously injured so I get back inside. After that incident, that Origins guy and me were like peas and carrots. He starts talking to me everytime he sees me about anything and everything. I guess he felt like we did a good deed together or something. Heck, it sure beats asking a bunch of gamers for their badges all day long.<br />
<br />
Anyway, I get back to the tournament for the last round<br />
<br />
Round: Five<br />
Opponent: Brett Meold<br />
Deck: Corsairs / Rohan totally teched against Forest Naz <br />
Good: This was a very relaxed game and luckily Corsairs is a great match up for me<br />
Bad: Pippin dies early since I once again am scared he has a Red Wrath in hand to kill Sam, Great Elf Warrior who I can’t afford to lose. <br />
Ugly: He doesn’t double to 7 when I’m at 6 which ends up being KEY since I can’t hurt his fellowship. He then allows me to choose one of two possible double moves (either 6-8 or 7-9) so that lets me win easily<br />
Result: FW site 9<br />
4-1<br />
<br />
So with that record, I come in 3rd place for the top 8 playoff. 1st is Kyle George and 2nd is Dan Jones in his highest-placing DGMA event ever I believe. Both Jones brothers did crazy well over the weekend. <br />
<br />
So I’m not sure who to play and I go outside with Dan Jones to see if that guy’s alright. He’s not around so I figure he’s fine and my cell phone rings. It’s the judges and they need to see me. Uh oh. <br />
<br />
Kirk England calls me over, put my decklist in front of me and throws my starting fellowship on top of it saying, “Find those in your decklist.” I’m close to saying, “isn’t that your job?” but instead opt for the more diplomatic, “they’re probably not there if you’re telling me this.” Turns out when I wrote up my decklist in Montreal a week earlier, I forgot to include my starting fellowship (Sam, Rosie and Maggot). So I get a decklist error and a gameloss which I’m half upset about until I find out that Dan Clark also got a decklist error which puts me in 8th place. So I still have a chance at this. <br />
<br />
I was lucky enough to get a copy of Dan Clark’s decklist and it’s one of the funniest things I’ve ever seen. Dan isn’t into LOTR as much as he used to be and this decklist was made with great haste and little motivation. Here are some awesome highlights from the decklist (note that these are actual entries):<br />
<br />
·	Ringbearer: Frodo  (note the lack of subtitle)<br />
·	The One Ring, Blue one<br />
·	Symble----- (since Dan didn’t even want to attempt to spell Simblemyne, he starts off trying and then just scribbles the rest)<br />
·	Legolas, Greenleaf x5  (remember this was a Standard format not Expanded)<br />
·	Sam<br />
·	Aragorn<br />
And my personal favourite:<br />
·	Sting, foil<br />
<br />
Awesome J<br />
<br />
Anyway, on the subject of decklist errors, I was debating if I wanted to challenge the decision to give me a gameloss when it’s so obviously an innocent mistake. I know of a few Level 4 judges that wouldn’t give a game loss for a mistake like that since it’s so obviously not cheating. But I decide not to make a fuss and just take my chances at getting paired up against Kyle George in round one. I’ve thought about that match-up after out last game and even asked him, “do you think that makes a good Day Two deck?” Since it’s so easy to adapt your play style against it. He says no, it makes a better day one deck and I agree.<br />
<br />
Quarter-finals<br />
Opponent: Kyle George<br />
Deck:Ultra-corruption, smeagol/dwarf<br />
Good: I start Tolman instead of Rosie and Maggot<br />
Bad: He kills Tolman almost right away with Enquea and Between Nazgul and Prey<br />
Ugly: I choke the entire way playing only Aragorn and maybe Bilbo, I double into site 9 with him at 7 thinking I can’t kill his fellowship<br />
Result: FW site 9<br />
<br />
I feel kinda bad since I figured without the decklist error, I would have played Kyle in the finals as opposed to the quarter-finals. It’s really too bad. Still, I’m happy that Adrian Westico moved up  his bracket straight to the finals after losing his first round to me and being forced to win out.<br />
<br />
Semi-Finals<br />
Opponent: Brad Hilton<br />
Deck: Forest Nagzul / Dwarf/Gondor mad site manipulation<br />
Good: Brad is a really nice gentle opponent. Smiles a lot and has a good sense of humour<br />
Bad: His really cute baby boy is in the stroller beside me looking at me with those baby eyes saying, “please don’t ravage my daddy.”<br />
Ugly: I proceed to ravage his daddy J<br />
Result: FW Shadow kill site 8  - actually it was a very close game. I didn’t really ravage him J<br />
<br />
So making me even more happy than making it to finals myself is seeing that 16 year-old Adrian Westico, friend of equally young Edwin Harris and Philip Marshall, has managed to win all his games after losing to me in first round. So he gets another shot at old man Sullivan. Let’s see what happens. I go into the game very confident since I know what to do. <br />
<br />
North American Continental Championship Finals<br />
Opponent: Adrian Westico<br />
Deck: Forest Nazgul / Noble Leaders<br />
Good: This kid totally rocks <br />
Bad: I never have to double move really against this deck and my fellowship can’t be killed when it single moves<br />
Ugly: He decides to double to 3 with only Toldea on the table. I reconcile into Lemenya, Nelya, Witch King and one or two Dark Approaches. I play them all! Boromir has to fight twice and gets 6 burdens while Faramir dies.<br />
Result: FW shadow kill site 4<br />
<br />
Oh my. Did I just win my first DGMA event? I think I did. It’s so late at this point that the only people left to congratulate me is Adrian, his friends and the DGMA judges, along with Kim Logie. It’s pretty late so Kirk is nice enough to drive me back to the hotel with Dan Jones and Paul Holbrook. I won a box of Reflections, a box of Siege of Gondor and a bunch of foreign language starters and boosters. I give all of that to Dan Jones since he wants it more than I do and I can’t imagine bringing all that home. Plus it would be too much work to sort all that when I don’t really need anything in those boxes (the only cards I really need are Frecas). I give away my Weta Busts and uncut sheets to Kim Logie and Kirk England since I don’t really want those either. I keep the HUGE pile of foils and masterworks legends that I won over the week as well as all those promos. I end up nabbing 5 Saruman Origins promos and 6 Vegas Pippins as well 2 Otsea Netherlands, 4 promo Legolas GTS exclusive and probably a few others. I’m going to make my home retailer in Joliette, Quebec very happy. <br />
<br />
I also won a free flight to GenCon which I already had bought anyway so Bojo says he’ll work something out. <br />
<br />
So back at the hotel, I’m all alone since everyone else has left the city. So I just crash and watch TV all night. <br />
<br />
Day Four<br />
Monday, July 4th, 2005 – Independence Day<br />
<br />
So I get up at 8 or so and treat myself to an awesome breakfast before grabbing the free shuttle to the airport. The flight back is uneventful save for one screaming little kid who starting going nuts once we entered Canadian airspace. Weird.<br />
<br />
Origins was a total blast and I can’t believe how it continues to be the only event that I do decent at. I’m anxious to see how GenCon goes for me this year. All of you reading this had better come to GenCon. These events should not be missed.<br />
<br />
<br />
Props:<br />
·	Chris Schoenthal for splitting the room with me and for providing lots of laughs and fun the entire trip. <br />
·	Fred Lafont for the Expanded deck that nailed me 1st place in the PSE day one and 5th overall. Un grand merci!<br />
·	Quentin for inspiring me to actually play hobbits. So glad that we’re both the Continental champs. See you at GenCon!<br />
·	Brian Fred who I always forget to give props to. <br />
·	Kirk England for those awesome Tim Horton’s runs in the morning<br />
·	Kyle George who would have been 2nd had I not made that decklist error<br />
·	Adrian Westico, Edwin Harris and Phillip Marshall for being three really great players for such younglings. You guys really tore up the competition over the weekend. Nice job!<br />
·	Paul Holbrook for running really smooth events and doing things exactly as they should be done.<br />
·	Kim Logie for, as usual, running smooth events.<br />
·	Mike Noonan for playing me so often and having a blast<br />
·	Steve and Dan Jones for being the best and placing the highest they’ve ever done (until Worlds this year, that is)<br />
·	Brad Hilton for putting up with me and playing a concentrated game even though his significant other and little one were waiting on the sidelines.<br />
·	Christian “Sting” for the fun match<br />
·	Dave Evans for that much needed fun match at the end of the PSQ<br />
·	Reed Mascola for being so inconsistent in his playing. He makes top 16 with Pipeweed then completely scrubs out of Continentals. Too funny J<br />
·	Dan Clark for being so adorable and for that hilarious deck list<br />
·	Emir for the great game and for always laughing<br />
·	Jonathan Benton for totally wrecking me and selling me on the idea that Dunland ain’t half bad<br />
·	Angela Desveaux for writing good music for unwinding between stressful rounds<br />
·	Seth for not doing so hot but having fun just the same<br />
·	Mike Girard for running a poker tournament and for other stuff I can’t remember<br />
·	Trevor McGregor for continuously bringing Lust around when I’m in the middle of a game<br />
·	Hayden for being super cool and the only guy to talk to (along with your buddy) at Char Bar<br />
·	Dawn cuz she’s my boss and I have to put her here otherwise I gotta work for JoyRide or something J<br />
·	Charles Hickey for inviting me to play poker with his friends<br />
<br />
Slops<br />
·	Barley’s for not knowing how to run a restaurant<br />
·	Getting game losses for simple innocent understandable mistakes on decklists. It’s just so archaic. <br />
<br />
See you all at GenCon! J<br />
